Emilio Aguinaldo - Wikipedia 

   - March 22, 1897, to November 2, 1897, president of the Biak-na-Bato Republic from November 2, 1897, to December 20, 1897, head of a dictatorial government from May 24, 1898, to June 23, 1898, and president of another revolutionary government from June 23, 1898, to January 22, 1899.[2] 

- b. Aguinaldo is honored by the Philippine Presidential Museum and Library as First President of the Philippines for his presidency of the First Philippine Republic. He had held prior positions as president of a revolutionary government from June 23, 1898, to January 22, 1899,, president of the Biak-na-Bato Republic from November 2, 1897, to December 20, 1897, and president of another revolutionaty government from March 22, 1897, to November 2, 1897. He headed a [3] 

- dictatorial government from May 24, 1898, to June 23, 1898 ~~;~~ That dictatorial government proclaimed Philippine independence from Spain on June 12, 1898. 

- c. It was the date that Aguinaldo formally swore an oath accepting the authority of the United States over the Philippines and pledging his allegiance to the American government after he was captured in March 23. 

- d. Miguel Malvar acted unofficially as head of the Philippine Republic after Aguinaldo was captured. However, Manuel Quezon, elected in 1935, is officially considered to be the next president following Aguinaldo ~~.~~ [4] 

- e. As officially recognized by the contemporary Philippine government; President of the Philippine Commonwealth in 1935 

- f. In the Philippine "Declaration of Independence" his maternal family name is given as Fami.[7][8] 

- g. The exact date of Aguinaldo's birthdate was March 22, 1869. It can be seen in National Historical [12][13][14][15] 

- Institute's marker in Aguinaldo Shrine, Kawit, Cavite. Some sources give other dates ~~.~~ [16][17] 

- h. The Mexican dollar at the time was worth about US$0.50 (equivalent to $19.35 in 2025) ~~.~~ [36][37] The _peso fuerte_ and the Mexican dollar were interchangeable at par. 

